Urinary tract infection (UTI): This is a bacterial infection that affects the urinary system, including the bladder and kidneys. Symptoms of a UTI may include fever, frequent urination, and burning or pain when urinating.

Pyelonephritis: This is a serious kidney infection that may require hospitalization. Symptoms often include fever, chills, back pain, and nausea and vomiting. Urine tests can help to identify bacteria in the urine. Blood tests can be used to assess kidney function and the severity of infection.

Kidney stones: Stones can be formed in the kidneys and pass through the ureters, causing pain. Fever and flank pain may also accompany kidney stones. Urine tests and imaging tests, such as a kidney ultrasound or computerized tomography (CT) scan, are usually needed to confirm diagnosis.

Glomerulonephritis: Inflammation in tiny filters (glomeruli) within your kidneys can lead to glomerulonephritis, causing microscopic blood to appear in your urine. This can also trigger swelling and high blood pressure. Fatigue and shortness of breath are also possible.

Lupus: Symptoms that are similar to kidney infection may occur in people with lupus, a disease in which the immune system attacks your body. If Lupus affects your kidneys (lupus nephritis), it could lead to protein in your urine. Tests include a blood test to detect antibodies specific to Lupus, a urinalysis, and a kidney biopsy to examine tissue under a microscope to look for abnormalities in kidney structures.

Polycystic kidney disease (PKD): PKD refers to an inherited disorder in which cysts develop within your kidneys, leading to enlarged kidneys, high blood pressure and kidney failure. Other possible signs include blood in urine and pain.

Sickle cell anemia: Blood vessel blockages occur in individuals with this inherited condition due to abnormally shaped red blood cells, possibly affecting other parts of the body, including the kidneys. Symptoms and complications associated with kidney disease may develop, such as high blood pressure and hematuria. Sickle cell anemia can be diagnosed via blood test and a family history review.

Alport syndrome: Alport syndrome is characterized by hearing loss alongside abnormalities like hematuria (presence of blood in the urine). This rare genetic kidney disorder may cause kidney damage in young adulthood. It can be screened through genetic testing and urine analysis. There’s currently no cure, so treatment depends on managing symptoms.

Diabetes: Uncontrolled high levels of blood sugar may cause kidney damage and protein in urine, leading to diabetic kidney disease (nephropathy). If left unmanaged, this can further progress into chronic kidney disease and kidney failure. It’s essential for people with diabetes to control blood sugar and blood pressure to protect their kidneys.

High blood pressure (hypertension): Uncontrolled blood pressure can lead to damage of your kidney’s tiny blood vessels over time and can decrease their function. Blood pressure readings, in addition to a urine test and possibly an imaging test of your kidneys (such as ultrasound), are necessary for a diagnosis.
